06648nam a22009615i 9783038211785DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20142014sz     fo  d z      eng d  a2014469623  a(OCoLC)953295004  a97830382117857 a10.1515/97830382117852doi  a(DE-B1597)246527  a(OCoLC)885338080  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aszcCH00aNA203b.B57 2014 4aNA2750b.A73 2014 7aARC0000002bisacsh04a72022300aArchitectural Atmospheres :bOn the Experience and Politics of Architecture /ced. by Christian Borch. 1aBasel : bBirkhäuser, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (112 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Why Atmospheres? -- tSpace, Place, and Atmosphere: Peripheral Perception in Existential Experience -- tUrban Atmospheres: Charting New Directions for Architecture and Urban Planning -- tThe Politics of Atmospheres: Architecture, Power, and the Senses -- tAtmospheres, Art, Architecture -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tPhoto Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArchitecture is increasingly understood to be a sensual, spatial experience, which means that the experience of buildings and spatial constellations is also a perception of atmospheres that are rated as positive or negative. Architects, planners, investors, and politicians must produce effects such as these according to intersubjective and communicable criteria, and not intuitively or randomly.Architectural Atmospheres addresses the growing awareness of the atmospheric dimension of architecture and provides a current, programmatic discussion of this topic. What possibilities does this approach open to architecture, what value does this knowledge have? Three essays and a conversation lead a cross-discipline discussion on the impact of architecture, and contribute to the debate first initiated by Peter Zumthor. The texts are accompanied by thirty-five color images that capture architectural moods in a variety of ways.Gernot Böhme is Professor Emeritus of Philosophy at Darmstadt Technical University and Director of the Institute for Practical Philosophy, e.V., Ipph, in Darmstadt, Germany.Christian Borch is Professor of Political Sociology at the Department of Management, Politics, and Philosophy, Copenhagen Business School, Denmark.Olafur Eliasson is a Danish-Icelandic artist. Eliasson incessantly explores our modes of perceiving. His work spans photography, installation, sculpture, and film.Juhani Pallasmaa is one of Finland's most distinguished architects and architectural thinkers.  aArchitektur wird vermehrt als ein sinnlicher Erfahrungsraum verstanden. So ist das Erleben von Bauten und Raumkonstellationen immer auch ein Wahrnehmen von positiv oder negativ gewerteten Atmosphären. Architekten, Planer, Investoren und Politiker sind darauf angewiesen, solche Wirkungen nicht intuitiv oder zufällig, sondern nach intersubjektiven und kommunizierbaren Kriterien zu erzeugen.Architectural Atmospheres greift das wachsende Bewusstsein für die atmosphärische Dimension der Architektur auf und liefert eine aktuelle, programmatische Auseinandersetzung mit diesem Themenfeld. Welche Möglichkeiten eröffnet dieser Zugang zur Architektur, wo liegt sein Erkenntniswert? Drei Essays und ein Gespräch verhandeln fächerübergreifend die Wirkungsmacht der Architektur und regen zu einer Fortsetzung der von Peter Zumthor initiierten Debatte an. Die Texte werden von rund 35 farbigen Abbildungen begleitet, die in vielfältiger Weise architektonische Stimmungen auffangen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitectsvInterviews. 0aArchitecturexPolitical aspects. 0aArchitecture. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aBorch, Christian, econtributo